To exit a C program, you can use the `exit()` function or `return` statement in the main function. Here's an example:

```c
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    printf("Hello, World!\n");
    return 0;
}
```

In this example, the `return 0;` statement is used to indicate that the program has executed successfully. The `exit()` function can be used to terminate the program immediately, regardless of where it is called from. Here's an example:

```c
#include <stdlib.h>

int main() {
    printf("Hello, World!\n");
    exit(0);
}
```

In both examples, the program will print "Hello, World!" and then exit. The number passed to `exit()` can be used to provide an exit status to the operating system. A value of 0 usually indicates success, while a non-zero value indicates an error.

You can also use `return` statements in other functions to exit those functions and return control to the calling function. If a function does not have a `return` statement, it will automatically return control to the calling function when the function's execution is complete.

If you want to stop the program from running due to an error or unexpected condition, you can use a `while(0)` loop or a `for(;;)` loop. These loops will immediately exit because their condition is always false. Here's an example:

```c
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    int i;
    for(i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
        if(i == 5) {
            printf("Error at line %d\n", __LINE__);
            while(1); // Infinite loop to stop the program
        }
        printf("Line %d\n", i);
    }
    return 0;
}
```

In this example, the program will print the lines 0 through 4, then print "Error at line 5" and stop running due to the infinite loop. The `__LINE__` macro is used to print the line number where the error occurred.
